Test suite (Rust port of `test/snippet.test.ts`) exercising snippet-body rendering and the two Plover/nvim build artifacts (`plover_keys`, `snippets`) produced from the real `dict.steno` corpus at the repo root.

The corpus is read live via `corpus()` (path `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../../dict.steno`), then expanded with `expand_dict` into `TypedEntry` values looked up by full stroke string via `by_stroke`. One test case — the single-landing `` `${%0}` `` template and its escaping behavior — can no longer be sourced from the corpus because the stroke it used to live at (`STKWR-LT`) now means something else (a `let` binding); `template_literal()` reconstructs the same `TypedEntry` by hand via `parse_template("`${%0}`", 1)` so the test still validates the renderer even though the corpus fixture is gone. Anyone updating `dict.steno` should know this hand-built entry exists specifically to keep that coverage alive independent of corpus contents — if `STKWR-LT` changes meaning again, this file doesn't need to change, but if the template-literal snippet rendering logic changes, both `template_literal()` here and the real renderer must stay in sync.

Key behavioral assertions encoded here (load-bearing, not just illustrative): function snippets renumber landing tabstops to tab order with `${0}` as the trailing exit and a literal `\}` before it; the `U`-prefixed one-liner variant (`STKWRUPBGS/...`) produces identical content but with no `\n`; free-type (`SKP`) constructs leave a tabstop at the type slot (asserted via literal `"): $"` substring and an exact tabstop count of 4); non-terminal partial entries (`PR-FLT` stroke) render with brackets stripped and zero `$` characters — no tabstops at all; and escaping rules require literal `$`, `}`, and `\` to be backslash-escaped while `${N}` tabstop syntax itself must remain unescaped.

`build_snippets` is checked for zero keyset collisions across the whole corpus, and every Plover-dict token is verified to (a) be wrapped in `SENTINEL_OPEN`/`SENTINEL_CLOSE` and (b) strip/resolve to a key present in `build.snippets`, with a sanity floor of >1000 total snippets — this last number will need bumping if the corpus is pruned significantly, and will silently keep passing if the corpus only grows.